Advantages and disadvantages of converting credits into Swiss francs
On the banking market, two offers for converting loans into lei in Swiss francs have already appeared, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when variable interest rates can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting the loans granted by Volksbank into francs, and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its own customers.
According to data compiled by analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest at lei, of 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Banca Transilvania’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of clients with loans in francs due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced with the value of the risk and administration commissions paid by the client, then an additional 22.5% reduction was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to the equivalent monthly plateau in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
BENEFITS
The main advantage of the lei coverage of loans in CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future franc increases, and the reimbursement of the credit will be made in the currency in which he collects his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that no reassessment of the property is made, no additional guarantees are required, and no further proof of income is required.
Basically, a new financial and legal analysis of the credit will not be made, nor will there be additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer a discount at the monthly rate, compared to how much customers pay before conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first few years is made up more of the interest, and the customer pays back very little of the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very low interest rates in the first three years seems advantageous for customers.
However, it is not known how this rate will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be greater than 3.25%, so overall, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all loans in lei with variable interest is that the ROBOR index will grow significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor index - CHF).
For example, ROBOR at three months is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached the value of 6%, in 2009, over 15%, and in a few days of 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, there may be other costs not mentioned in the initial offer.
