Other participants in the meeting are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the tobacco control section of the PHE.
The group’s research work “convincingly masks” the lack of “solid evidence of the harmful effect that most products have by most criteria,” McKee and Capewell said.
However, none of these links or limitations are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell said PHE’s claims that “to date there is no evidence that e-cigarettes are a factor encouraging smoking among children or non-smokers” are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of the health department at PHE, says that he has responded to BMJ’s claims in the past.
He said, “E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking.”
One in two people who have smoked all their lives loses their lives because of this addiction.
All the evidence suggests that e-cigarettes pose a comparatively minor health risk, but we need to continue to study their long-term effects.
