Violinist David Grimal: In Bach’s time there were no world tours.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, artists and not commercial representatives.
The French violinist David Grimal is one of the great artists of our time, known not only as a soloist but also as the initiator of a less ordinary, quite "weird" project, as he himself says, Les Dissonances - an orchestra formed by international soloists and talented musicians, who perform a symphonic repertoire without having a conductor on it.
Les Dissonances was this year at the Enescu Festival with two performances: a performance, on Sunday, in which the soloist was David Grimal, the founder of the orchestra, and a Monday, when the cellist Xavier Phillips was in the foreground, the works composed by Enescu were not lacking.
Both performances, held on the stage of the Athenaeum, showed the audience a different way of interpreting classical music.
Les Dissonances appeared on the music scene in 2004, being, at the time, the only classical musical ensemble in which there was no conductor.
The conductor is the most important musician for musicians.
It’s true, on the one hand, musicians need an education either to become soloists or to become performers in an orchestra – I’m talking about instrumentalists, not composers.
They are trained as "specialized workers".
They feel like they need a conductor.
On the other side of the stage, for the audience, all the musical fetishization focuses on the conductor.
And so, the business, the music industry, does its marketing.
We are no longer talking about music.
So if we look at this world, we have on the one hand skilled workers, which is stupid, and an audience that can’t listen, but has to look, which is stupid again,” Grimal said.
The violinist recounts that this change in the way he makes music came after the "musical disappointments" of his solo career.
I was like a high-level athlete who had to do the same exercise all over the world with different orchestras, to make a lot of money and to bring money and music industry.
Ten years ago, when I was about 30, I found this very depressing, because I no longer found human creativity and fraternity in this system.
So I haven't found any sense to continue on this path.
So I decided to create Les Dissonances.
This happened in 2004, and at the time no one did this without a conductor: "The musical world, extremely conservative, did not want such projects".
“How do you imagine doing marketing with a collective of musicians where there is no ego anymore?” the artist asks.
David Grimal acknowledges that Les Dissonaces represents "a luxury", noting that none of the musicians who are part of the orchestra depend on the success of this project to live.
In the 10 years of the existence of the ensemble, the lack of a conductor did not prove to be a hindrance in the musical act: "Interestingly, the more we sang a more complex repertoire, the simpler it seems, because all musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not only in the role", Grimal argues, adding as to the Sunday performance "I was on stage".
In Grimal's opinion, the Enescu Festival is a "very courageous one", precisely because he invited Les Dissonances: "An extraordinary festival, where there are the largest orchestras in the world who sing and 3 times a day, and in the midst of these orchestras you invited this strange group".
In a temple of orchestral tradition, such as the Enescu Festival, there is a place and interest in something different, breaking barriers.
Speaking of Enescu’s work, the violinist admits that he feels the Romanian music of the famous Roman composer, so he did not need a special approach when he introduced works by Enescu into his repertoire.
Grimal notes that Enescu's music is very instinctive, but this is what happens when we talk about George Enescu and Romanian music, "because there is also a George Enescu who made French music".
Grimal advocates for changing the way classical music education is done, considering that "musician work, as it is organized today, has an epoch of death" and that "the future of music represents music itself".
We don't need to go around the world five times a year if it's useless.
In Bach's time, there were no world tours.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, who were artists and not commercial representatives.
For me, organizing concerts, festivals, tours, releasing albums, all are formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they are done in the service of music.
If not, we are in a system where creativity suffers, no longer has freedom.
