At the most anticipated meeting in recent years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank’s meeting room, will be seen a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, Fed Chairman, and her colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above all else.
The Central Bank has been given a double task by Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the X-factor in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be rid of the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in place since the end of 2008.
Even though most data points to a strong growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already wary of adding volatility by raising the benchmark to federal funds — even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed’s decision, which in itself is causing instability in the financial market.
Approximately half of the economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg predicted an interest rate hike this week.
But financial markets are expecting the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30 percent.
This would indicate a fall on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers mitigated the blow by promising that it would take a long time for the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The surge was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep interest rates stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising for the Fed to raise interest rates at this time,” Lonski said.
If Fed policymakers were to do so, they “should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.”
Other experts said an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percent this month, the first small step toward slow tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an interest rate hike this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to fibrillate late this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below its record high in May as investors feared the slowdown in China’s economy would bring down global growth.
The market declined somewhat this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed policymakers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate growth.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and news of the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be more firm in the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they almost have no data to rely on after the events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s major interests, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank’s influence has been huge.
The mere allusion of then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “tighten” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly twinned, it is expected that Fed officials will not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at welfare management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that “The Fed has an oversized history of reacting to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to economic bases.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Commission for the Open Market, a decision-making body that supported interest rate hikes, offered the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that hit Asia prompted the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the limited identification implications for U.S. development,” Mr. Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to the declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The last turbulent period did not rise to that level at all, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to end up in a situation where we’re afraid of an interest rate hike because markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take action prematurely.
