Weight-loss surgery may be helpful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be sustained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those following nonsurgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize the mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18,5 to 24,9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy — in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical diabetes treatments remained at nearly the same level, namely 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean A1c haemoglobin level decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycemic control”—reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels—did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 compared to 14.2 kg), experienced more considerable decreases in BMI (7.4 compared to 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% compared to 2.1%) and had a higher probability of complete remission (16 % vs. 2.1%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on overweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMIs below 35 who were interested in the procedure.
“This is where this paper is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long before we’re urging people to take this seriously,” she said.
