On Wednesday, the government approved the “National Immigration Strategy for 2015-2018” and the “Action Plan for the current year”, documents considered to be “another stage that Romania is going through as part of efforts to modernize the process of managing immigration on national territory”, according to a press release.
The strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect the policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
Considering the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are envisaged for the unitary and coherent management of the situations determined by the possible occurrence of an influx of illegal immigrants on the territory of Romania, generated by crisis situations of a political, social, economic or military nature.
"The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay special attention to citizens from countries with potential migration or that may harm national security," the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reviving the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and escalating the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, stricter controls of the legality of the residence of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the appropriate application of removal and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the overall strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access on the Romanian territory of third-country nationals who respond to employment needs, facilitating access of third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the Action Plan for 2015, the Government considers that it is "a means by which concrete activities are established that lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migration phenomenon".
