The connection between Osama bin Laden and the crash of the crane in Mecca
Saudi authorities have announced that the Saudi giant Binladin Group, belonging to the family of Osama bin Laden, is "partly responsible" for the crash of a crane on Friday on the Great Mosque in Mecca, in which 107 people died.
According to an investigative commission, the company did not "comply with safety regulations," the Saudi news agency (SPA) reported.
The company’s directors were banned from leaving the country until the investigation was completed.
The company will also be excluded from new public contracts.
The construction company is owned by the family of the former leader of the Al-Qaida terrorist network, Osama bin Laden.
The company was founded by Osama bin Laden’s father 80 years ago and is currently run by the brother of former terrorist leader Bakr.
Binladen Group has been working for 4 years on the expansion of the Great Mosque to accommodate more pilgrims.
The crash occurred Friday night during a storm, when a crane, likely unbalanced by strong wind gusts, crashed on the eastern side of the roof of the Grand Mosque in Mecca.
As a result of the accident, 107 people died and nearly 400 were injured.
