Users of the network, which has reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long sought the opportunity to express their negative emotions or empathy with something sad.
Zuckerberg said it was not comfortable for people to "like" current events, such as the refugee crisis, or the death of a family member.
“You may not feel comfortable liking that post,” the Facebook representative said.
The version of a new button on Facebook was not well received by everyone.
“There is already enough hate on Facebook and on social media,” Atiq Haneef of Afghanistan said on the New York Times Facebook page, where the article on the subject was posted.
"I'm going to 'Dislike' the 'Dislike' button," he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist in Atlanta, said there was nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, a social media analyst at eMarketer, said it’s hard to imagine that a single button can convey a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she argues, the election campaign in America is approaching, and the “Dislike” button would create a total disaster.
