Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
Due to economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in the last decades can no longer continue in the following years.
Until Saturday, probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn is.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the UK Labour Party, many wonder to what extent the election of a politician who is not in a decision-making position after all can affect us.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical leftist leader of the post-war Labour movement.
Declared Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once asked Tony Blair, then prime minister, to remove the royal family from Buckingam Palace), a ferocious anti-American and a sympathizer of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events by Britain's "Russia Today" television channel), and of the renegade Hamas and terrorist movements.
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a real tragedy, ISIS is close to preferring the United States.
Following the model of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like the ones he was saying and promising and Tsipras in Greece until the moment he came to terms with the real world and the economic legacies.
The economic program of the new Labour leader foresees, among other things, massive renationalizations and the printing of money as a solution to finance development projects and to cover very generous social benefits.
Sure, some may wonder why the solution with the printing of money is not unanimously adopted on the globe, we would then have a global general prosperity!, but who else to avoid such details.
Of course, we can tax the bankers, who have become a kind of enemy of the left, to the blood, but from what has been seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of the mandates of Mitterrand and Hollande.
The extra sums are quickly swallowed up by the generous, coverless promises made by populist demagogues.
Margaret Thatcher once said, “The problem with socialism is that at some point other people’s money runs out.”
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance to ever become prime minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in his convictions as the new party leader, failed miserably in the election.
And then there was still a working class in Britain, in the classical sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were significantly more influential than they are now.
Given the new industrial landscape, in which services are dominant across the workforce, and extensive automation has made the industry massively in need of highly skilled labor, Corbyn’s rhetoric has a limited appeal.
But even from opposition, it can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In his latest issue of the Financial Times, he believes that Corbyn’s election increases the chances of Brexit and Britain’s exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and you look at the refugee crisis shaking from the EU’s foundations, you come to an explosive mix.
And not just for the UK.
But if the British decide following the referendum, which is due to take place by 2017, to leave the Union the loss of symbolic capital for the whole European project and the deep fault lines created within it by the Euro crisis and now that is why refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leave room for the most worrying scenarios.
Especially since for a whole series of member states, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin becomes more and more the dominant actor anyway).
It is true, the British business environment, the City, are strong advocates for the country’s stay in the EU.
But today’s Europe is no longer the one of the past.
There are many resentments, which increase in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, as we have recently seen in Jean Clude Junker's speech, increasingly tends to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of Member States by consulting only a few European powers, mainly with Germany.
And this is happening at a time when electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigration groups that are at the same time Eurosceptic is growing spectacularly across the continent.
In other words, the negatively charged emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever before.
Which is why the Financial Times concludes when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation that departs from the national interest.
If the voters make the brain decision, then the UK will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn’s victory reminds us of the power of emotion in current politics.
However, Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we will see a more pronounced integration of the euro area, which will push most of the states in the region and to the periphery of interest and that of the decision-making process in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States fuel their populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
Due to economic and demographic causes, the prosperity enjoyed in the last decades, the generous social benefits, can no longer continue the same in the following years.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Euro-immigration zone, both provoked by hasty decisions that only took into account integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulences on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and can greatly affect the situation of Romania.
And it’s hard to exclude something from the point of view of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
